cs.CL, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.NE, cs.IR. 

This paper is about parsing text into its Abstract Meaning Representation (AMR), which is a task in natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely category. Within cs.CL, the subcategories that are relevant to this paper are cs.CL (NLP) and cs.CL (Information Retrieval). 

The paper proposes a novel approach for AMR parsing that emphasizes capturing the main ideas of a sentence, which involves predicting new nodes and their connections to existing nodes in a top-down fashion. This approach involves machine learning techniques, such as joint prediction, and can be seen as a form of artificial intelligence (AI). Therefore, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a likely category. 

The paper also evaluates its model on the latest AMR sembank and achieves state-of-the-art performance, which involves using machine learning algorithms to optimize the model. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) are also likely categories. 

Finally, the paper involves processing and analyzing text data, which is a task that is relevant to information retrieval (IR). Therefore, cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is also a possible category.
